DENGUE/DHF - PHILIPPINES: BACKGROUND
************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed/html>
Date: Mon, 17 May 1999 21:26:37 +0300
From: Stephen A. Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background information on dengue in the Philippines was
extracted from the GIDEON software program:
Dengue hemorrhagic fever was first reported in the Philippines in 1953, and
the world's first epidemic of DHF was reported in the Philippines during
1953 to 1954. At that time, 53% of Filipinos were seropositive (62% of
children in urban Manila).
Year DHF cases fatal
1954 74 10
1955 96 13
1956 750 >70 (numbers for the Manilla region)
1957 152 19
1958 94 34
1959 125 73
1960 551 40
1961 1,459 34
1962 134 62
1963 189 74
1964 759 169
1965 652 109
1966 9,384 250
1967 1,371 105
1968 1,116 115
1969 1,336 103
1970 922 83
1971 438 34
1972 1,570 83 (numbers for Manilla)
1973 591 62
1974 1,665 153
1975 603 42
1976 460 174
1977 376 224
1978 358 213
1979 438 18
1980 627 103
1981 123 8
1982 305 31
1983 1,684 130
1984 2,545 89
1985 2,096 210
1986 839 30
1987 859 27
1988 2,922 68
1989 305 14
1990 588 27
1991 1,865 20
1993 5,715
1994 5,603
1995 7,413
1996 14,648
1997 12,600 300
15,650 cases (7,755 hospitalized; 276 deaths) of dengue/DHF were reported
during January to September 1998 - with epidemics in Ballesteros (Cagayan
province), San Antonio and Jaen (Nueva Ecija province), Dumaguete city
(Negroes), and Malaybalay (Bukidnon province).
